) The Coordinating Committee shall determine the actual legitimate cost of the multi-purpose project after the construction of the original structures and/or any addition thereto and to make the final allocation to the different entities concerned of their share of the cost of the project. For purposes of pre-determination of the depreciation or amortization and interest charges that will enter into the expected unit production costs of (1) electric power, (2) industrial water, and (3) irrigation water, the Coordinating Committee shall also make suitable allocation of the overall construction cost estimates to each phase of the project, prior to or during the course of construction as the need for such allocation may arise, taking into consideration the commercial values of each of the products from the project and assigning a proper value to the economic and social benefits to be derived from flood control.

SEC. 7. For the proper coordination of the activities of the different entities concerned in the Ilog River Multi-Purpose Project, the Multi-Purpose Committee created under Administrative Order Numbered Sixty-five of September twenty-seven, nineteen hundred fifty-four is hereby authorized to serve as the implementing agency of this Project.

SEC. 8. (

a

) The National Power Corporation is hereby authorized to secure loans from financing institutions or construction corporations for the dollar funds needed to finance its share of foreign currency requirements of the Ilog River Multi-Purpose Project, and of the Fertilizer Plant.

It is also authorized to borrow from proceeds of the sale of bonds under Republic Act Numbered One thousand the peso funds corresponding to its share of the cost of the multi-purpose project and of the fertilizer plant;

(

b

) The funds needed by the Bureau of Public Works as its share of the cost of the multi-purpose project for th flood control and irrigation phases shall be taken from economic development bonds issued under Republic Act Numbered One thousand.

SEC. 9. This Act shall take effect upon its approval.

Approved, June 16, 1955.
